{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558881/1946021701/0632.xml":{"full_text":"SU-ANN SHOES ARE\nFITTED CORRECTLY\nSu-Ann Shoe store, 109 1-2 N.\nFront stret, specializes in correc\ntive fitting of men\u2019s, women\u2019s and\nChildren\u2019s shoes in the proper arch\nsupports besides carrying a com\nplete line of shoes for all members\nof the family.\nG. W. Strawn and J. D. Fennell\nare partners in the Su-Ann Shoe\nstore which was founded in 1940.\nin 1941 the store was located in\nits present position, and in 1945 the\ninterior of the store was complete\nly remodeled. Stawn acts as mana\nger of the store.\nAmong the lines carried in Su\nAnn store are: Paris Fashions,\nCorinne and Natural Poise shoes\nfor ladies, Red Goose and Acrobat\nshoes for children, and Robler,\nFortune and Roberts, Johnson and\nRand shoes for men. For boys, the\nstock includes official Boy Scout\nshoes, Sky Rider and Buster Brown\nshoes.\n\u201cThe business outlook for Wil\nmington is very good,\u201d says\nStrawn. \u201cWe will have to have\npayrolls to keep up employment\nand to keep the retail business\nhealthy. We have the housing,\ntransportation facilities and clim\nate that should induce new manu\nfacturers to come to Wilmington.\nThen, too, there is the resort busi\nness that should help the retail\nmerchant in the summer months.\u201d\nSu-Ann Shoe shop boasts a shoe-,\nrepair shop in the store which re\npairs, rebuilds all types of shoes\npromptly and expertly. There are\n12 regular and extra employes in\nthe store.\nCAROLINA B L\nBEGAN ON $2.50\nThe Carolina Building and Loan\nassociation was organized in Feb.\nruary, 1912, with an initial invest\nment $2.50 by the late L. W,\nMoore. In the first series of thd\nassociation there were 114 sub\nscribers to shares, the offices being\nlocated at 123 1-2 Princess Street\nin a space aproximately 6 1-2 x\n20 ft. After the second year larger\nquarters were necessary and the\nentire building at 123 Princess\nStreet was leased.\nSo great was the progress of the\ninstitution that in 1918 they moved\nto 205 Princess Street, and in 1921\nto its present location.\nThe Carolina reached its first\n\u201cMillion Dollar\u201d mark in January,\n1924, and on its 25th Anniversary\nhad assets of one and a half mil\nlions. The \u201cTwo Million Dollar\u201d\nmark was reached in December,\n1938; the \"Three Million Dollar\u201d\nI\nOWNER-MANAGER\n1\nGEORGE N. STRAWN, above, is\nowner-manager of the Su-Ann Shoe\nstore, 109V2 N. Front street.\nmark in December, 1943, and the\n$3,900,000.00 in December, 1945.\nThroughout all of these years the\nCarolina has provided a systematic\nplan of investment and mortgage\nloan second to none. Countless\nthousands have become home\nowners through the B L plans\nand millions have been saved and\ninvested through the Carolina\u2019s\nsystematic plans of investment.\nThe association has kept pace\nwith the times. It was the first\nBuilding and Loan Association in\nWilmington to issue full paid and\nrunning shares; the first to bring\nthe 12 1-2 cents series or 12-year\nloan plan to the local borrowing\npublic, and now it is operating\nunder the monthly direct reduction\nloan plan, which is so appealing\nto borrowers. The institution has\navailable for lending more than\nthree millionf dollars in cash and\nits record for mortage loans in\nJanuary of this year total' more\nthan $100,000.00 actually made.\nThe Carolina has every faith in\nthe future of Wilmington and in the\noutlook for both home construction\nand home financing, a spokes\nman declared. \u2018\u2018We welcome the\nopportunity of serving the return\ning G. L\u20194 three of whom are now\nconnected with this institution,\ntherefore naturally we feel a keen\ninterest in their needs,\u201d he con\ncluded.\nThe first Wyoming territorial\nconventions of the Republican and\nDemocratic parties were held in\nAugust, 1869.^\nSan Juancita, Honduras, keglers\nbowl on two mahogany alley beds.\nFull Employment Debates\nMay Grow More Important^\nEmergence Of Unemploy\nment As Big Issue Test Of\nOf Business Stability\nBy Cambridge Associates\nWhether governmental machin\nery can be developed to even out\nfluctuations in the business curve\nappears now to be a question that\nwill not be settled until unemploy\nment again becomes a serious is.\nsue. Sometime, however, the at\ntempt will be made and the cur\nrent debate will attain new sig\nnificance.\nThe formidably titled Murray\nWagner Thomas-O\u2019Mahoney bill\naroused much controversy. One oi\nits chief novelties was the pro\nvision that would establish an an\nnual survey of business needs and\nprospects and attempt to gea;\ngovernment spending to the re\nquirements of the times.\nEven in its original form the bill\ndid not guarantee \u201csixty mUlioi:\njobs.\u2019\u2019 The planning board pre\nsumably had the difficult task oi\ndefining \u201cfull employment.\u2019\u2019\nFull Employment\nOpposition: to this so-called Full\nEmployment legislation was based\non the continuing and increased\ninjection of government authority,\nthe possibiity that governmenl\nspending would be excessive and\npolitics dominated, and that nc\nfurther legislation was necessary\nto give the government the righl\nto increase or decrease expendi\ntures for necessary governmenl\nworks as the situation demanded,\nWhether this specific piece oi\nproposed legislation was suited tc\nthe purpose will not be argued\nhere. It does appear certain thal\nwhen unemployment mount!\nabove six million there will be in\ntensified pressure for governmenl\naction. It will be desirable, seem\ningly, if the problem is considered\nbefore emergency steps have tc\nsubstitute for better considered\nmeasures.\nThe Argument\nMany economists believe thii\nthe \u201csixty million jobs\u2019\u2019 goal is\nhigher than is necessary or desir\nable. During the war, with nearly\neleven million of the best segment\nof the labor force in uniform,\nmiracles of production were ac\ncomplished by a working popula\ntion that numbered less than 6!\nmillion at its peak.\nObviously, longer work week!\nwere the rule than have beer\nfound efficient in peacetime but i1\nis also true that many of these\nworkers were p h y s i c a lly ill\nequipped and hurriedly trained foi\ntheir jo-bs. The same volume oi\nproduction in peacetime, using\nmore efficient labor accustomed\nto conforming to good industrial\nstandards, might easily be\nachieved with several million less\nworkers.\nSocial Standpoint\nFrom the social viewpoint, it is\nnot desirable to have the normal\nhomemaker of the family working\noutside the home. Neither should\nvery young people or the aged be\nconsidered a regular part of the\nlabor force, according to most\nmodem thinking. It could well be\nthat \u201cfull employment\u201d by the\nstandards which would provide\noptimum social welfare as well as\nadequate production of all eco\nnomic needs would be nearer 45\nmillion than 60 million. Such an\nobjective seems a possibility for\nthe near future but both Industry\nand government have the duty to\ncontinue development of methods\nthat will not permit employment\nto drop below that figure. 1\nSTANLEY JEWELRY\nHIGHLY REGARDED\nAaron D. Harris, co-owner and\npresent manager of Stanley\u2019s Jew\nelers, is proud of the fact that his\nstore is known as the friendly\njewelers\u201d to customers in Wil\nmington and adjacent areas.\nLocated at 109 Princess street,\nStanley\u2019s was established in April,\n1941, by Samuel Shavitz. Harris,\na co-owner, also is associated with\nStratford Jewelers, Statesville\nStanley\u2019s features nationally fa\nmous watches Elgin, Hamilton,\nLongines, Gruen and Bulova as\nwell as 1847 Rogers silverware,\nSimmons jewelry and diamonds of\nguaranteed quality. Also sold are\nWestinghouse radios, General\nElectric irons, toastmasters and\nRemington razors.\nThe store is a member of the\ncredit association.\nBesides Harris, who resides with\nhis family at 1815 Grace street,\nStanley\u2019s staff is made up of\nJames O. Simpkins, veteran of\nfour years in the armed forces,\nand Helen Mae Bryan, head of the\njewelry department. Simpkins and\nMiss Bryan both are lifelong resi\ndents of Wilmington.\nPerhaps Stanley\u2019s outstanding\ncharacteristic is its courteous serv\nice and the excellent quality of\nmerchandise.\nWhen cooking fruits, add some\nsalt and you will find less sugar\nis needed.\nOUR POST-WAR\nPLANS\nINCLUDE YOU! j\nTo Assure Wilmington and vicinity of a prosperous future of expansion and\ngrowth the WILMINGTON CHAMBER OF COMMERCE has outlined a 4-Point Program\nfor Progress with these objectives.\nIMake a determined bid for industrial expan\nsion in order to obtain more jobs at better\nwages.\n2 Create and encourage methods of increasing\nretail sales in the post-war period.\n3 Take a more active part in Wilmington civic\naffairs.\nk\n4 Offer full facilities of the Chamber of Com\nmerce to all Wilmington citizens in an effort\nto help them with their problems.\nTO CARRY OUT THE PROGRAM EFFECTIVELY YOUR CHAMBER\nOF COMMERCE IS TAKIHG THE FOLLOWIHG STEPS\n\n(A) A program of work through cooperative action and plan a schedule of today\u2019s activities in the\nlight of tomorrow\u2019s needs. (B To sell Wilmington to Wilmingtonians by backing Industrial Properties,\nInc., financially; to build plants for new industries thus creating higher employment. (C) To provide\nservices to established industries. (D) By organized effort seek to improve business of wholesale and\nretail merchants. (E) Promote and increase tourist and resort trade. (F) Participate in civic ac\ntivities of a community-wide importance in solution of which business and professional people can\nmake special contribution toward civic improvements.\nCHAMB i OF\nWoodrow Wilson Building, 4th and Princess Wilmington, N. C.\nI\nW H AT'S NEW\nI N\nBLOCKS CANTFADE SHIRTS\np\nIhis is the Buttonhole Job\u2014Girl operating two machines at a time can turn out shirts\nwith buttonholes at an average rate of 1500 daily\n1\nll\nPictured, two operations in shirt making\u2014Girl at right is \u201csetting\u201d sleeves to shirt, while girl in front \u201cfells\u201d sid\u00ab\nseams. Each of the girls averages 800 shirts daily in their operation.\nBACK AGAIN BETTER THAN EVER\nBLOCKS CANTFADE SHIRTS HADE TO PRE WAR STANDARDS\nFULL CUT FULL LENGTH TAILS, GRIPPER FASTENERS AND\nLAUNDERED STANDING COLLARS.\nDURING THE WAR YEARS OUR RESOURCES AND MANUFACTURING FA\nCILITIES WE DEVOTED TO MAKING SHIRTS FOR THE ARMY AND NAVY.\nNOV\u2019, WITH THE RETURN OF PEACE OUR PLANT WILL\nMORE AND BETTER THAN BEFORE SUPPLY YOU WITH\nSHIRTS YOU\u2019LL PROUDLY WEAR.\nSouthland Manufacturing Company\nWILMINGTON. N. C.","height":"27532","width":"20580"}}
